<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="693" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1421,644,1059]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,644,668]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">Identification.</emphasis>
The SVL is up to 
<quantity box="[1184,1277,645,669]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" unit="mm" value="180.0">180 mm</quantity>
. The body is large, with the dorsum greenish overall, but turning yellow after the first monsoon shower. We did not see any bright-yellow individuals with neon blue vocal sacs and instead only say a few individuals with some yellowish coloration on the flanks and dorsum. We noted that some frogs retain their yellowness throughout the breeding season. The feet are fully webbed. This frog is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Jerdon, 1853)" baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[840,1114,928,952]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[840,955,929,952]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. crassus</emphasis>
(Jerdon, 1853)
</taxonomicName>
; however, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[1229,1342,929,952]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[1229,1342,929,952]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species with a very limited range, and has oval spots on the lower limbs rather than the stripes of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Daudin" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[1233,1362,1000,1023]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigerinus">
<emphasis box="[1233,1362,1000,1023]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. tigerinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The call is wheezing, nasal, and growl-like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1420,1078,1208]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,908,1078,1102]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">Habitat.</emphasis>
This species was seen in semi-aquatic habitats and on the edges of perennial lakes and other water bodies. It is also known from secondary forests lined with acacia plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="693" type="distribution">
